# Comment Only What The Code Can't Say

Comments are a maintenance burden, not a free good: they are re-read on every
pass, they drift out of sync, and a stale/obvious comment costs more than no
comment. Write the FEWEST comments needed for a reader to understand what the
code alone cannot. More comments is NOT better.

## Do NOT write a comment that

- Restates what the next line(s) of code plainly do.
- Repeats what a well-named function / variable / type already says.
- Explains language or stdlib mechanics a competent reader already knows.
- Echoes an adjacent error message, log string, or test name.

## DO write a (short) comment when

- The **why** is non-obvious: a trade-off, workaround, ordering constraint,
  subtle invariant, or "looks wrong but is intentional".
- Behavior depends on something not visible here (another goroutine, a remote
  contract, a protocol/hardware quirk).

When in doubt, leave it out and improve the name instead. Keep the comments you
do write short (see [short-comments.mdc](short-comments.mdc)).

## Example

<bad>

```go
// TestMain requires DEX_TEST_POSTGRES_URI — the Postgres store tests must run
// against a real Postgres, never silently skip (a skip would falsely report
// PASS when the URI is missing). The Makefile excludes this package ...
func TestMain(m *testing.M) {
	uri := testURI()
	if uri == "" {
		fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, "DEX_TEST_POSTGRES_URI must be set to run the Postgres store tests")
		os.Exit(1)
	}
	...
}
```

The error message and the `os.Exit(1)` already say all of this; the comment
only restates the code.

</bad>

<good>

```go
func TestMain(m *testing.M) {
	uri := testURI()
	if uri == "" {
		fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, "DEX_TEST_POSTGRES_URI must be set to run the Postgres store tests")
		os.Exit(1)
	}
	...
}
```

</good>
